# Breakout Reflection

## By Skylar Anthony

# What were you experimenting with with your prototype? 	

The idea I had for my prototype was a game you would want to play when you didn’t have wifi. In my head, I imagined those games that get advertised as an ad when you lose a level on a game like Candy Crush. I wanted to make a game that didn’t have levels necessarily but had more of a limitless approach. I wanted it to be a game that you pulled out when you were waiting for the elevator or waiting to take off on the plane. I experimented with 3 different modes; a standard breakout style game, a game where the bricks fall from the top of the screen, and if the ball drops you lose a life, and an infinity mode where the same happens but you don’t lose a life.

# 

# What did you learn from your prototype?

This was the first time I ever programmed anything in my life so I learned a lot. I used a book as well as videos to write the scripts. As time went on I was able to distinguish the different parts of the scripts and rely less on the internet to program and type out certain things. An example is if there was something such as ball speed that I wanted to access in the inspector, I would change it from a private int to a public one.

I also learned to back up my work because I had to end up doing the entire thing over due to an error with Unity, GitHub and myself.

# 

# Did you learn anything from your playtesters in class? What?

Getting able to play other student’s games was a great experience for me because it showed me all the possibilities of different things that I could implement in my game. My first couple of prototypes are very basic versions of breakout but the more I saw my classmates prototypes, the more I was inspired to try and research how to do different things.
